# Coding Standards & Best Practices

## File Organization & Naming
- Use **PascalCase** for component files (e.g., `UserProfile.tsx`)
- Use **camelCase** for service files (e.g., `loginService.ts`)
- Use **kebab-case** for route folders (e.g., `privacy-policy/`)
- Keep related files grouped in logical directories
- Use descriptive, meaningful file names

## TypeScript Guidelines
- Always use TypeScript for all `.ts` and `.tsx` files
- Define interfaces in the `types/` directory
- Use proper type annotations for all functions and variables
- Export types from [types/UserType.ts](mdc:types/UserType.ts) and similar files

## Component Structure
- Prefer functional components with hooks
- Use proper imports order: React, Next.js, external libraries, internal modules
- Implement proper error handling and loading states
- Use React.memo() for performance optimization when needed

## Styling Conventions
- Use **Tailwind CSS** for all styling
- Follow mobile-first responsive design principles
- Maintain consistent spacing and color schemes
- Use semantic class names and group related styles

## Authentication & Security
- All authentication logic should go through [middleware.ts](mdc:middleware.ts)
- Use environment variables for sensitive configuration
- Implement proper error handling for API calls
- Validate user inputs on both client and server sides

## Service Layer
- All API calls should be handled in the `services/` directory
- Use consistent error handling patterns across services
- Implement proper TypeScript interfaces for API responses
- Cache API responses when appropriate

## Code Quality
- Follow ESLint rules defined in [eslint.config.mjs](mdc:eslint.config.mjs)
- Use meaningful variable and function names
- Write JSDoc comments for complex functions
- Keep functions small and focused on single responsibilities
